        body: 'Ngozi Eze operates a corrugated carton factory in the Ariaria industrial layout of Aba, Abia State. Her facility runs a 1.4-metre-wide single-facer corrugating machine, a manual flute laminator, a two-colour flexographic printer, a rotary die cutter, and a stitching machine. With 22 employees across production, sales, and administration, she produces approximately 120 tonnes of corrugated cartons monthly, serving food processors, soap manufacturers, pharmaceutical distributors, and hardware traders across the South-East and South-South zones of Nigeria. In late 2025, Ngozi won a contract to supply 50,000 branded cartons monthly to a mid-sized beverage company launching a new malt drink line in Aba, Owerri, and Uyo. The contract price was NGN 680 per carton for a custom-designed RSC box with three-colour print, food-grade inner liner, and auto-lock bottom. She estimated her production cost at NGN 510 per carton based on her standard kraft paper consumption rates, ink usage, and labour allocation. The NGN 170 margin per carton, multiplied by 50,000 units, suggested NGN 8.5 million in monthly gross profit, a transformative contract for her operation. The reality proved more complex. The auto-lock bottom design required a custom rotary die that cost NGN 1.8 million and took three weeks to fabricate. The three-colour print required precise registration that her flexo press achieved only after extensive setup time, wasting approximately 2,200 sheets per production run during make-ready. The food-grade liner required a specific adhesive applied at controlled temperature, and her glue consumption ran 40 percent above estimate because the liner absorbed more adhesive than the standard kraft she typically used. When Ngozi reconciled actual costs after the first three months of production, her true cost per carton was NGN 635, leaving a margin of only NGN 45 per carton instead of the NGN 170 she had projected. The contract was still profitable, but barely, generating NGN 2.25 million monthly instead of NGN 8.5 million. The gap between projected and actual margin existed because Ngozi cost estimation was based on averages rather than job-specific calculations. She did not have historical data on die-cutting setup costs by box complexity, make-ready waste by print colour count, or adhesive consumption by liner type. Every custom job was quoted using rules of thumb that worked for standard boxes but failed on complex designs.'
